{"actual_usd":0.160195,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":295,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31154,"reply":"\"I mean— not the actual moment of resurrection itself, if that's what you're asking.\" *I push my glasses up and squint a little into the morning light across the square, trying to keep the answer plain.* \"A camera would've seen a sealed tomb earlier, then later an opened tomb, the stone moved, guards either gone or wrecked by fear, grave clothes left behind, and then very confused people arriving in waves.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along the edge of the bench once.* \"If you stitch the Gospel accounts together without trying to sand off the rough edges, the camera version is basically: before dawn, women come to the tomb; there's an earthquake and an angelic appearance around the stone being moved; the tomb is found open; Jesus is not there; messengers announce he's risen; the women run and tell the others; Peter and John go look; later Jesus starts appearing to people alive, in body, over the course of that day and after.\"\n\n\"The key frustrating part, if you're wanting literal footage, is this: nobody is described as standing there watching Jesus' body reanimate inside the tomb like a medical clip. The event is real, physical, and empty-tomb visible— but the instant itself is mostly given to us by its aftermath.\" *I glance at you.* \"If you want, I can do the next step and give you the most concrete camera-timeline I think the texts support, beat by beat.\"","rolling_24h_usd":72.24503499999997,"run_id":"14e59170-9600-4efd-9ebf-ecf5761f8cdb"}
